ersome approach. A final section deals with games that have an infinite number of pure strategies for the two players. Throughout, the theory is generously illustrated with examples, and exercises test the reader's understanding. A historical note caps off each chapter. For readers familiar with the calculus and with elementary matrix theory or vector analysis, this book offers an indispensable store of vital insights on a subject whose importance has only grown with the years.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 31. Jan 2022) 0aBUSINESS and ampxECONOMICSvEconomicsvTheory. 0aGame theory. 0aMathematicsvGame Theory. 7aMATHEMATICS / Game Theory.2bisacsh  aAbstract algebra.  aAddition.  aAlgorithm.  aAlmost surely.  aAnalytic geometry.  aAxiom.  aBasic solution (linear programming).  aBig O notation.  aBijection.  aBinary relation.  aBoundary (topology).  aBounded set (topological vector space).  aBranch point.  aCalculation.  aCardinality of the continuum.  aCardinality.  aCartesian coordinate system.  aCharacteristic function (probability theory).  aCombination.  aComputation.  aConnectivity (graph theory).  aConstructive proof.  aConvex combination.  aConvex function.  aConvex hull.  aConvex set.  aCoordinate system.  aDavid Gale.  aDiagram (category theory).  aDifferential equation.  aDimension (vector space).  aDimensional analysis.  aDisjoint sets.  aDistribution function.  aEmbedding.  aEmpty set.  aEnumeration.  aEquation.  aEquilibrium point.  aEquivalence relation.  aEstimation.  aEuclidean space.  aExistential quantification.  aExpected loss.  aExtreme point.  aFormal scheme.  aFundamental theorem.  aGalois theory.  aGeometry.  aHyperplane.  aInequality (mathematics).  aInfimum and supremum.  aInteger.  aIterative m